From 0000000000000000000000000000000000000000 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: subarr-subgen <subarr@localhost>
Date: Tue, 21 Jul 2026 16:40:00 +1000
Subject: [PATCH] 0033: honour SKIP_STARTUP_SCAN at the startup call site only

Upstream 2026.06.5 added SKIP_STARTUP_SCAN and implemented it as an early-out
inside transcribe_existing(). That function has two callers: the lifespan boot
thread and the POST /batch endpoint. subarr drives subgen entirely through
/batch, so on upstream semantics an operator who sets SKIP_STARTUP_SCAN=1 (a
reasonable "do not walk my whole library on boot" setting) would silently get a
no-op for every transcription subarr requests, with a zero-count response and no
error anywhere.

This moves the gate to the boot call site, which is what the variable name
actually describes. Upstream intent is preserved (no scan at startup) and
explicit on-demand requests keep working. Pairs with patch 0003, which omits the
in-function early-out.
---
diff --git a/subgen.py b/subgen.py
index 7b5fbaa..599b173 100644
--- a/subgen.py
+++ b/subgen.py
@@ -222,7 +222,15 @@ AUDIO_EXTENSIONS = (
 @asynccontextmanager
 async def lifespan(app: FastAPI):
     if transcribe_folders:
-        threading.Thread(target=transcribe_existing, args=(transcribe_folders,), daemon=True).start()
+        # [PATCH] SKIP_STARTUP_SCAN is gated HERE, not inside transcribe_existing().
+        # Upstream 2026.06.5 put the check inside the function, but /batch calls the
+        # same function, so the env var also silenced every on-demand request. Gating
+        # at the boot call site keeps upstream's intent (no scan on startup) while
+        # leaving explicit /batch dispatch working.
+        if skip_startup_scan:
+            logging.info("SKIP_STARTUP_SCAN is enabled - skipping the startup scan of existing files.")
+        else:
+            threading.Thread(target=transcribe_existing, args=(transcribe_folders,), daemon=True).start()
     yield
 
 app = FastAPI(lifespan=lifespan)
